<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Pet only weapons that are actually good. <br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Tons of farmable weapons out there that are good. Yaks and gnoll whips being just two of them.  I'd rather see them allow us to get the weapons back somehow. Like reclaim weapons and pet poofs or some such.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Pet only armor with stats that actually add to the pet's stats<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
This one only be good if they allow us to summon a bagfull like the bags of armor we can summon now.  I don't want to have to summon 9 pieces of equipment on top of everything else I have to cast already.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Pet &quot;lures&quot;<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
The water pet casts a spell that LOOKS like ice why doesn't it HIT like a cold spell?<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  More beneficial pet buffs<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Again this goes back to the fact I don't want to have to keep casting more and more spells on my pet or for my pet.  Soon we'll have nothing to do but cast buffs for pet for an hour.  My resists are all over 100 and it seems to work fine.  Pet used to get slowed religously in fungus grove but now it is very VERY rare he does.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Utility Pets<br>
<br>
These pets would work like any other pet, which means we could not have another pet up and have any of the utility pets up.<br>
<br>
A pet at lvls 20, 39, and 54 that roots. Same cast time as the wizard basic root, same resist rate/length of hold. This pet would have approximately 10 hps at lvl 20, 45 hps at lvl 39, and 85 hps at lvl 54. This pet would disappear within 15 seconds after summoning if not directed to attack. This would give us the ability to walk through an area and maybe not have to gate if attacked. This pet would cast root immediately upon being sent at a mob.<br>
<br>
A pet that increases our mana regen. This pet would not attack a mob as normal if we were attacked.<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
If you wanted to be a wizard then you should have made one. Verant has already stated Mage will never get root. Learn to deal with it.  I personally don't want Flappy flying around my head just to get mana regen.  rods and transons and a form of clarity work just fine for me.<br>
Not saying is a bad idea, god knows I'd use if given to us but of all the ideas here this one has the lowest chance of ever seeing the light.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> General things non pet related<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Personally I like that the pet takes no exp from the group instead of getting the buffs from the group.  After all as long as a group member is within MELEE range the pet doesn't even get hit, so why bother buffing it?  They took the exp penalty off for us. If we got pets buffed with group then I'd forsee the penalty coming back.<br>
<br>
Love the phantasmal idea.<br>
<br>
The drop command would be nice but tis one I can take or leave.  I use the slimline inventory for the new UIs and since I'm never looting during raids, cept the odd item I am awarded a full inventory is just easier for me atm.<br>
<br>
 <p><p><a target="_blank" href="http://www.tritonguild.com"><img src="http://www.daveshirley.org/neil/mantriarodsig.jpg" border="0"></a><br>
<a target="_blank" href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=91891">Stuff a Broken Down Old Mage Uses</a></p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/uayanlaxev.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Ayanla Xev</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Magician</span><br>  Posts: 2<br> <font color=#333333>(10/7/02 7:49:59 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerfrm32.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=361.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   re: Ideas</span><hr size=1> It's not that I want root so much as I want some method of not being slaughtered immediately (or gating) if I'm caught without a pet up. I would just like the option to run through an area and not have to decide on defense or invisibility.<br>
<br>
If I'm running through an area invis and something sees through, or it drops (rare since I have the fixed duration invis), it is silly that I have zero options aside from running or gating. I've tried the &quot;channel through&quot; method, and that didn't work so well *grin* I have kited mobs around and killed them without a pet but it's rare that actually works since most of our nukes have a rather long cast time and the mob is on me before I've finished casting. Generally if something sees through my invisibility I either gate or train the nearest zone. I HATE having to train an area because I have no other option aside from gating back to my bind (which is almost always nexus)<br>
<br>
I don't want to be a wizard, I thought that was pretty clear from most of my suggestions, since 90 percent of them revolve around our pet. I like being a pet class, but by the same token I do not feel that should mean I have no means of defense. The idea of the utility pet was thrown up when I was talking with my husband one night. I agree that traditional root is not within Verant's vision of a mage, and I understand how it would throw a significant advantage to the chain pet people, but I do not feel the &quot;utility pet&quot; root would give us any significant advantage other than the ability to maybe not train a zone line.<br>
<br>
Explain to me why Necromancers, the other int caster pet class, have Root, Snare, Feign, Harmshield, Shadow Step, and Gate and we have Gate. I've heard the reasoning of &quot;well our pets are stronger&quot; and quite frankly that doesn't cut it with me. I'm not talking about a measure of defense I could use when my pet is up, I'm talking about a measure of defense for situations where my pet is not up. I do not feel that would give us a significant advantage, and I'm not even asking for a method that is guaranteed, just a shot at defending myself is all I ask for.<br>
<br>
Pure caster wise let's look at defense (not counting gate)<br>
<br>
Shaman<br>
Root: 2 second cast<br>
<br>
Druid<br>
Root: 2 second cast<br>
Snare: 2.25 second cast<br>
<br>
Cleric<br>
Root: 2 second cast<br>
Stun: several, various cast times, shortest is 1 second<br>
Divine Aura: 1 second cast<br>
<br>
Enchanter<br>
Root: 2 second cast<br>
Stuns: lots, various cast times, shortest is 1 second<br>
Rune: Longer cast but can be put up ahead of time<br>
Mez: lots, various cast times, but short<br>
<br>
Necromancer<br>
Root: 2 second cast<br>
Feign Death: 1.5 second cast<br>
Harmshield: 1 second cast<br>
Shadowstep: 1 second cast<br>
Darkness line: Various cast times, but relatively short<br>
<br>
Wizard:<br>
Root: 2 second cast<br>
Shadowstep: 1 second cast<br>
Snare: 2.5 second cast<br>
<br>
Magician:<br>
Pet: 10 second cast<br>
<br>
I am the only one who sees some disparity in the defensive ability of the caster classes? Someone please explain to me how this is balanced and how giving magicians another method of defense would somehow make us powerful gods or something. <br>
